name: Kepler-173
scenarioDescription:
The Kepler-173 Exoplanetary System

Kepler-173 is a star with 0.8719999999999999 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.95 times its radius. It is located 2783.38 light years away from the solar system.

Kepler-173 is known to have 2 exoplanets in orbit around it.

Kepler-173 b

Kepler-173 b was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its discovery was announced in 2014-03. Its semi-major axis is 0.05 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. It takes 4.26 Earth days to complete an orbit around its host star, Kepler-173.

The mass of Kepler-173 b is 1.77 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-173 b is 1.29 that of Earth. At 1.77 Earth masses, Kepler-173 b is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.

Kepler-173 c

Kepler-173 c was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its discovery was announced in 2014-03. Its semi-major axis is 0.07 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. It takes 8.01 Earth days to complete an orbit around its host star, Kepler-173.

The mass of Kepler-173 c is 8.12 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-173 c is 2.43 that of Earth. At 8.12 Earth masses, Kepler-173 c is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.
